## What I Worked On Today

ISO 27001 is an international standard for building what is called an **Information Security Management System — or ISMS**. The name sounds technical but the idea behind it is fairly straightforward: rather than treating security as a one-time project or a list of controls to implement and forget, ISO 27001 asks organizations to build a living system that continuously identifies risks, responds to them, and improves over time.

What sets ISO 27001 apart from something like PCI DSS is its flexibility. PCI DSS says "here are 12 requirements — implement them." ISO 27001 says "here is a process for figuring out what your specific risks are — and then selecting the controls that actually address those risks." That requires more judgment, more organizational maturity, and more ongoing effort. But it also means the security program you end up with is tailored to your actual environment rather than a generic baseline.

The framework is organized around a few key elements:

**Risk Assessment** is the starting point. Before you can decide what controls to implement, you need to understand what your actual risks are. What assets are most sensitive? What threats apply to your environment? What vulnerabilities exist? What is the potential impact if something goes wrong? For an OpenMRS deployment, this means thinking carefully about patient records, system availability, and the specific ways an attacker might try to compromise the system.

**Annex A Controls** is a library of 93 security controls organized into categories — access control, cryptography, physical security, incident response, supplier relationships, and more. Importantly, you do not implement all 93. You use your risk assessment to decide which controls are relevant to your environment and document your reasoning for the ones you choose not to implement. That documentation is itself part of the standard.

**The Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle** is what makes ISO 27001 a management system rather than just a control framework. Plan your security approach. Implement it. Check whether it is working. Act on what you find — fix what is broken, update what has changed, improve what could be better. Then repeat. Security is never finished, and ISO 27001 is designed around that reality.

