## What Actually Clicked for Me

The Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle was the thing that clicked most for me today — specifically because of what it implies about how organizations often approach security in practice.

A lot of organizations treat security like a project with a start and an end date. You implement controls, you pass an audit, you move on. ISO 27001 explicitly rejects that model. The Check and Act phases exist to make sure that what was implemented is actually working and that it stays relevant as the threat environment changes. That is not a one-time effort — it is an ongoing operational commitment.

What I found interesting is that this connects directly back to something from Day 6 — the NIST RMF's Monitor step. Both frameworks are independently arriving at the same conclusion: security programs that do not include continuous review and improvement will eventually fall behind the threats they are trying to address. The frameworks are different in structure but consistent in philosophy.

The other thing that clicked was the concept of the **Statement of Applicability** — the document where an organization lists all 93 Annex A controls, states which ones they are implementing and why, and explains their reasoning for any they are excluding. I had not encountered anything quite like this in the other frameworks I have studied. It forces a level of intentional decision-making and documentation that I think would be genuinely valuable — not just for auditors, but for the security team itself.

