## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2017 Equifax data breach** — one of the largest and most consequential breaches in history, exposing the personal data of approximately 147 million people. The cause was a known vulnerability in the Apache Struts web framework that had a patch available for months before the breach occurred. Equifax had simply not applied it.

What this case illustrates from an ISO 27001 perspective is a failure in the Check and Act phases of the PDCA cycle. The vulnerability was known. The patch existed. The process for identifying and applying patches — vulnerability management — had broken down somewhere between detection and action.

An organization genuinely operating an ISMS under ISO 27001 would have vulnerability management as an active, monitored process — not something that happens when time allows. The Annex A controls include requirements for technical vulnerability management specifically because this kind of failure is so common and so costly.

I found it sobering that the breach was not caused by a sophisticated zero-day attack. It was caused by a known vulnerability with a patch sitting unused. That is a process failure, not a technical one — and it is exactly the kind of failure that a well-maintained management system is designed to prevent.

